"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.1.6\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.1.6</span> Sickle</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">חֶרְמֵשׁ</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chermesh)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut16:9\">DEU 16:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut23:26\">DEU 23:26</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַגָּל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(magal)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer50:16\">JER 50:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Joel4:13\">JOL 4:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">δρέπανον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(drepanon)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark4:29\">MRK 4:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:14\">REV 14:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:15\">REV 14:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:16\">REV 14:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:17\">REV 14:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:18\">REV 14:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:18\">REV 14:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:19\">REV 14:19</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0320_cutting_grain_sickle.jpg\" alt=\"Man cutting grain with a sickle\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Man cutting grain with a sickle (The Pictorial New Testament, The Religious Tract Society 1881, Public domain)</figcaption></figure>The sickle was a large, curved knife used for cutting ripe grain. It had a short wooden handle (15–20 centimeters, 6–8 inches).</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0321_sickle.jpg\" alt=\"Sickle\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Sickle (© Juan R. Lascorz, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The implement was swung in a circular motion close to the ground, cutting off the grass or grain. Using the sickle required bending over in order to cut close to the ground, while the longer handle of the scythe allowed the worker to stand erect (see also <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">2.15.1 Scythe (chariot weapon)&lt;REALIA:2.15.1&gt;</a>).</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Where there is no receptor-language term for “sickle,” translators may often use a descriptive phrase, such as “curved knife for cutting grain,” “reaping hook,” or “machete for reaping.” In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:0\">REV 14:0</a> the word sickle is used in idiomatic expressions that could be confusing to the reader. For example, in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:15\">REV 14:15</a>, rather than the literal “Put in your sickle, and reap” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>), it may be clearer to say “Use your sickle and reap the harvest” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>). The long-handled scythe was unknown in ancient Israel. Where a translator must choose between a short-handled implement and a long-handled one, the former will be more accurate.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
